2.5 AI‑Driven Autonomous Systems for Aerospace MRO

2.5.1 Drone‑Based Visual Inspection

The application of autonomous drones for aircraft exterior inspection has matured rapidly. Donecle, a French company pioneering this domain, combines automated UAVs with computer vision algorithms to inspect aircraft quickly and reliably, increasing aircraft availability by accelerating inspections and providing data analysis solutions for maintenance optimisation. Industry projections indicate that by the end of 2025, all key players are expected to have obtained regulatory approvals for full‑scale deployment.

Emerging technologies include hyperspectral imaging drones capable of detecting degradation and damage that the human eye cannot see (PAM APAC, 2025), and AI‑based diagnostic systems covering the entire drone lifecycle from manufacturing to operational deployment. Techno‑economic analyses of smart hangar inspection operations have developed actionable methods for balancing accuracy, coverage and budget in autonomous robotic inspection systems within MRO hangars.

The ROI case for drone inspection is well documented in industry literature. For a mid‑sized MRO facility, autonomous drone inspection can achieve 80 % reduction in inspection time and a 3.4x return on investment within 12 months. However, these figures are based on European and North American labour costs. This research will calibrate the ROI model to Moroccan labour rates (€25/hour compared to €100‑120/hour in Europe) to produce realistic projections.

2.5.2 Predictive Maintenance

Predictive maintenance enabled by AI and digital twins has become a strategic priority for global aerospace operators. The literature documents several recent advances. The UK Royal Navy has expanded AI predictive maintenance to its fixed‑wing aircraft fleet using the “Motherlode” analytics platform to predict failures, reduce unnecessary maintenance and improve fleet availability. Odysight.ai has developed an AI‑powered visual analytics platform that converts visual data into actionable maintenance intelligence, enhancing flight safety and reducing unscheduled downtime. The US Marine Corps has selected Virtualitics to apply predictive technology to accelerate maintenance on MV‑22 Osprey squadrons.

At the MRO Middle East 2026 conference, industry experts emphasised that AI will integrate data across the “MRO continuum” for better fault resolution, with AI providing full operational context to proactive parts removal. Academic research has proposed data‑driven frameworks for maintenance prediction under sparse observational data, implementing and comparing two distinct methodologies for aircraft components. A complex adaptive systems perspective has been proposed to bridge the theory‑practice gap in AI‑driven automation of aviation equipment inspection, addressing data limitations, model performance degradation and deployment challenges.

The economic case is compelling: between 2019 and 2025, easyJet avoided 1,343 cancellations and 171 major delays by utilising predictive maintenance AI (easyJet annual reports). Industry estimates suggest that such strategies can cut unscheduled repairs by 30‑40 %. For the Moroccan aerospace cluster, which aims for a 1 % reduction in overall operational costs, this represents approximately €25 million in annual savings.

2.5.3 Hybrid CNN‑LSTM Architectures for NDE

The technical core of this research lies at the intersection of composite materials engineering and AI‑driven NDE. Recent literature has focused on hybrid architectures that capture both spatial and temporal features from multi‑modal sensor data.

A comprehensive review of AI for image‑ and signal‑based NDT in aerospace structures (Donatus, 2025) presents a structured synthesis organised around the two dominant data paradigms: image‑based and signal‑based inspection. The review specifically identifies hybrid CNN‑LSTM architectures and emerging transformer models as the frontier of this field.

In the specific domain of aircraft composite inspection, researchers have proposed an improved Feature Enhancement Network (FEN)‑CNN‑BiLSTM method for impact damage depth prediction in civil aircraft composites using multi‑domain terahertz spectroscopy, addressing the issue of low accuracy and stability in traditional CNN‑based defect depth prediction. Machine learning‑enhanced ultrasonic phased array inspection for aerospace CFRP composites has been evaluated using a hybrid method combining time‑of‑flight diffraction with advanced signal processing. Studies have also investigated the application of machine learning in ultrasonic transducer inspections leveraging Lamb waves to improve defect characterisation in aerospace composite structures.

Recent experimental results demonstrate that hybrid CNN‑LSTM systems achieve up to 98 % accuracy in pattern recognition for complex damage detection, significantly outperforming individual AI techniques. However, the literature reveals a critical gap: nearly all studies are based on laboratory‑generated datasets or proprietary industry data. No study has addressed the challenge of deploying such models in a lower‑resource setting like Morocco, where labelled defect data is scarce and industrial infrastructure is evolving. This research will address this gap through transfer learning from public datasets (e.g., GDXray, Aircraft Visual Inspection Dataset) and synthetic data generation via digital twins.

2.6 Innovation Policy Instruments for University‑Industry Collaboration

2.6.1 Innovation Vouchers

Innovation vouchers are a widely used policy instrument for stimulating SME engagement with public research institutions. The literature documents their effectiveness across multiple jurisdictions. Enterprise Ireland’s Innovation Voucher Programme provides SMEs with vouchers to purchase academic support from registered knowledge providers, building links between public knowledge providers and the business community. The UK’s BridgeAI programme offers £15,000 innovation vouchers to help SMEs identify and implement AI solutions through technical feasibility studies and early‑stage AI adoption guidance delivered by the Hartree Centre. Shanghai has implemented innovation vouchers effective from September 2025 through August 2030 to stimulate innovation among SMEs and enhance the high‑quality development of the science and technology services sector.

Evidence from evaluation studies indicates that innovation vouchers produce significant positive impacts: firms using vouchers for IP‑related projects have four times more patent applications in their first year; vouchers correlate with higher business survival rates and increased R&D tax credit usage; and regional roadshows for similar SME support programmes successfully connect entrepreneurs outside capital cities, building trust and activating regional innovation ecosystems.

For Morocco, the Startup Venture Building programme (MAD 1.3 billion, approximately $140 million) provides a potential funding source for a sector‑specific AI Innovation Voucher scheme. However, the literature reveals that no study has designed or evaluated an innovation voucher scheme tailored to the Moroccan aerospace context. This research will fill this gap by delivering a feasibility study for a €20,000‑50,000 AI Innovation Voucher scheme targeting GIMAS SMEs.

2.6.2 Joint Laboratories

The joint laboratory model has been extensively documented in the innovation studies literature (Perkmann & Walsh, 2007; Breschi & Lissoni, 2009). Successful joint labs exhibit common characteristics: co‑location of researchers, shared IP agreements, multi‑year funding commitments, and governance structures that balance academic freedom with industrial relevance. The A*STAR‑Rolls‑Royce‑SAESL joint lab described above is a paradigmatic example, with a five‑year collaboration programme supported by S$60 million in combined investment.

However, the literature on joint labs in lower‑middle‑income countries is sparse. Most studies focus on developed economies. This research will contribute to filling this gap by designing and documenting the establishment of a tripartite Integrated Research Unit (IRU) in Morocco—a scaled‑down joint lab appropriate for the resource constraints and institutional context of an emerging aerospace cluster.

2.6.3 Skills Passports and Micro‑credentials

Digital skills passports and micro‑credentials have emerged as a flexible mechanism for workforce upskilling in response to rapidly changing technological requirements. The European Union has developed comprehensive competence frameworks (DigComp, LifeComp, GreenComp, EntreComp) that serve as the basis for stackable micro‑credential systems across member states. The Malaysian Aerospace Centre has implemented a fully funded micro‑credential programme offering training in Aircraft Maintenance Licensing, Non‑Destructive Testing, Digital Engineering (Dassault Systèmes), and On‑Job‑Training placements. The Starmaster Space Education Centre has launched a suite of over 25 micro‑credential programmes designed to fast‑track skills in space science, engineering, and deep‑technology, with the explicit goal of creating “a scalable, future‑ready workforce” through micro‑credentials and flexible pathways.

For Morocco, a Skills Passport for AI‑augmented inspection technicians would align with the national “Maroc IA 2030” target of training 200,000 graduates in AI skills. However, the literature does not contain any study of skills passport implementation in the Moroccan aerospace context. This research will deliver a pilot Skills Passport programme for 20‑30 technicians from IMA or AEROSUP, with a target 20 % salary premium.

2.7 Research Gap and Contribution

The literature review reveals a significant research gap at the intersection of four domains: Moroccan aerospace industrial development, AI‑driven autonomous systems for MRO, global cluster innovation models, and innovation policy instruments. No existing study:

1. Proposes a quantified, PhD‑executable roadmap for deploying AI‑driven autonomous systems in the Moroccan aerospace MRO context, calibrated to local labour costs and regulatory constraints;
2. Designs a tripartite joint lab model (IRU) specifically for an emerging aerospace cluster, with explicit mechanisms for SME engagement and technology transfer;
3. Evaluates the feasibility of an AI Innovation Voucher scheme for Moroccan aerospace SMEs, grounded in primary data from GIMAS members;
4. Develops and pilots a Skills Passport micro‑credential programme for AI‑augmented inspection technicians in Morocco.

This thesis addresses these gaps through the research questions articulated in Chapter 1. The following chapter (Chapter 3: Methodology) describes the research design, data collection methods, development of the hybrid CNN‑LSTM architecture, validation metrics, and ROI calculation approach that will be employed to answer these questions.

Chapter 3: Methodology

3.1 Introduction

This chapter presents the research methodology employed to address the three research questions formulated in Chapter 1. The study adopts a design science research (DSR) approach, which is particularly suited to engineering-oriented PhD research that aims to create and evaluate an artefact—in this case, an AI-driven autonomous inspection system for aerospace MRO—while simultaneously generating prescriptive knowledge about the conditions for its successful deployment (Hevner et al., 2004; Peffers et al., 2007).

The chapter is organised into ten sections. First, the research philosophy and overarching design are justified (Section 3.2). Second, the case study approach is detailed, including the rationale for selecting Midparc/Nouaceur as the primary empirical setting (Section 3.3). Third, the data collection strategy is described, covering primary industrial data, public datasets, synthetic data generation, and stakeholder interviews (Section 3.4). Fourth, the development of the hybrid CNN‑LSTM architecture for non‑destructive evaluation is presented (Section 3.5). Fifth, the validation metrics for the AI model are specified (Section 3.6). Sixth, the ROI calculation methodology is outlined, calibrated to Moroccan labour costs (Section 3.7). Seventh, the methods for the AI Innovation Voucher feasibility study and Skills Passport pilot are described (Section 3.8 and 3.9). Eighth, the contingency plan for drone regulation uncertainty is detailed (Section 3.10). Ninth, ethical considerations and risk mitigation are addressed (Section 3.11). The chapter concludes with a summary of the methodological framework (Section 3.12).

3.2 Research Philosophy and Design

3.2.1 Pragmatist Paradigm

This research is situated within a pragmatist research paradigm. Pragmatism prioritises the practical consequences of research and recognises that different research questions may require different methodological approaches (Creswell & Creswell, 2018). This philosophical stance is appropriate for a study that seeks not only to advance theoretical understanding of AI for aerospace NDE but also to produce a deployable prototype, a validated ROI model, and actionable policy recommendations.

The pragmatic orientation of this research is reflected in its mixed‑methods design: quantitative data (inspection times, defect detection accuracy, sensor readings) are combined with qualitative data (semi‑structured interviews with MRO engineers and policy makers, document analysis of regulatory texts) to provide a holistic understanding of both technical feasibility and institutional readiness.

3.2.2 Design Science Research Approach

DSR is a problem‑solving paradigm that seeks to create innovative artefacts while simultaneously generating knowledge about the problem domain and the artefact’s utility (Hevner et al., 2004). DSR is particularly well‑suited to this research because the goal is not merely to describe or predict phenomena but to intervene in the Moroccan aerospace ecosystem by designing, building and evaluating an AI‑driven inspection system.

The DSR process followed in this research comprises six steps (Peffers et al., 2007):

1. Problem identification and motivation: The low R&D intensity of the Moroccan aerospace sector, the talent bottleneck, and the absence of AI‑driven autonomous inspection systems in local MRO facilities (Chapter 1).
2. Definition of objectives for a solution: A functional autonomous inspection prototype achieving >95 % defect detection accuracy and a 60–80 % reduction in inspection time, validated in a live industrial setting.
3. Design and development: The creation of the hybrid CNN‑LSTM architecture, the integration with the physical platform (drone or ground‑based), and the development of the software pipeline.
4. Demonstration: Laboratory testing of the prototype using controlled specimens, followed by a pilot deployment at a partner facility.
5. Evaluation: Quantitative assessment of detection accuracy, inspection time reduction, and ROI, as well as qualitative assessment of user acceptance and institutional barriers.
6. Communication: Documentation of the artefact and the design principles in the PhD dissertation, journal publications, and a policy brief.

3.2.3 Mixed‑Methods Design

The research employs an explanatory sequential mixed‑methods design (Creswell & Creswell, 2018). Quantitative data collection and analysis (Phase 1 baseline efficiency metrics, Phase 3 pilot performance data) are followed by qualitative data collection and analysis (semi‑structured interviews with MRO engineers, policy makers and industry managers) to explain the quantitative results and to identify barriers and enablers for scaling.

3.3 Case Study Selection

3.3.1 Primary Case: Casablanca Aerospace City (Midparc/Nouaceur)

The primary empirical setting for this research is the Casablanca Aerospace City (Midparc/Nouaceur). This location was selected for four reasons:

1. Concentration of GIMAS members: Approximately 150 GIMAS member firms are located in or around Midparc, providing access to a diverse range of potential partner firms.
2. Proximity to research infrastructure: The proximity to UM6P (including the Toubkal supercomputer) and the AI Movement facilitates access to compute resources and AI expertise.
3. Presence of MRO facilities: Midparc houses several MRO facilities that perform regular exterior aircraft inspections, providing a relevant operational context for prototype deployment.
4. Accessibility: The location is accessible from the author’s home institution, enabling regular on‑site visits (the target of ≥40 % of research time, as committed in Chapter 1).

3.3.2 Partner Selection Criteria

At least one GIMAS member firm will be recruited as a research partner. The selection criteria for the partner firm are:

· MRO or manufacturing operations: The firm must conduct regular visual inspections of aircraft exteriors or composite components, providing a relevant use case for the prototype.
· Commitment to co‑location: The firm must agree to co‑locate one industry engineer with the PhD researcher for at least 10 hours per week during Phase 2 and Phase 3.
· Willingness to share data: The firm must agree to share anonymised inspection logs, defect images (where available), and operational efficiency metrics.
· Intellectual property agreement: The firm must sign a memorandum of understanding (MoU) that includes a provisional IP agreement (joint ownership of any patent arising from the research).

As of the commencement of this research, two GIMAS firms have expressed interest in partnership. Formal MoUs will be signed during Phase 1 (Months 0–6).

3.3.3 Comparative Context

While the primary focus is on the Midparc case, the research also draws on comparative contextual data from two additional sources:

· Toulouse (France): Interviews with two MRO engineers working at a Toulouse‑based facility will provide benchmarking data on inspection times, defect detection rates, and AI adoption in a mature aerospace cluster.
· Singapore (A*STAR): Document analysis and remote interviews with two researchers affiliated with A*STAR’s ARTC will provide insights into the operational model of a successful joint lab.

These comparative data are not intended to constitute a multiple‑case design in the traditional sense but rather to contextualise the Moroccan findings and to extract transferable design principles.

3.4 Data Collection

3.4.1 Primary Industrial Data

Baseline efficiency data (Phase 1) : During the first three months of the research, the current manual inspection process at the partner facility will be observed and documented. The following metrics will be recorded for a minimum of 20 inspection events:

· Total inspection time (from arrival of aircraft/component to completion of inspection report)
· Number of defects detected (by type: corrosion, cracks, lightning strikes, others)
· False positive rate (inspector‑flagged defects later deemed non‑critical)
· Number of inspectors involved per shift
· Lighting conditions and environmental variables

All data will be anonymised. No proprietary maintenance records will be extracted; only summary metrics will be retained.

Pilot deployment data (Phase 3) : During the 6‑month pilot deployment, the same metrics will be recorded for inspections performed using the AI‑driven prototype, enabling a direct before‑after comparison. In addition, the following system performance metrics will be logged automatically:

· Inference time per image (milliseconds)
· Detection confidence scores per defect
· Number of defects detected (by type)
· False positives and false negatives (validated by a certified inspector)

3.4.2 Public Defect Datasets

To address the challenge of limited labelled defect data (discussed in Section 3.10.2), the research will leverage three public datasets for transfer learning and pre‑training:

1. GDXray: A publicly available X‑ray image dataset containing annotations for casting defects, welds and baggage inspection. While not aerospace‑specific, the defect morphologies are transferable.
2. Aircraft Visual Inspection Dataset (AVI) : A limited dataset of aircraft exterior images with defect annotations, available for academic research.
3. DAGM 2007: A synthetic dataset of texture defects designed for benchmarking machine learning algorithms.

3.4.3 Synthetic Data Generation

Following best practices documented in the literature, synthetic defect data will be generated to augment the limited real‑world dataset. The synthetic data generation pipeline comprises three steps (Wang et al., 2024; Biondani et al., 2025):

1. Digital twin construction: A digital twin of a representative aircraft fuselage section or composite panel will be created using CAD software (SolidWorks or Blender). The twin will include geometric models of typical defect types (cracks, corrosion pitting, lightning strike damage).
2. Defect injection: Using a custom Python script, synthetic defects will be rendered onto the digital twin surface under varying lighting conditions, camera angles and surface reflectivity.
3. Image rendering: The resulting scenes will be rendered as synthetic images using a physically based rendering engine (e.g., Blender Cycles or Unreal Engine), producing labelled image‑mask pairs suitable for training semantic segmentation models.

The synthetic dataset will comprise at least 5,000 images, with defects uniformly distributed across the three target categories. This approach is consistent with recent research demonstrating that data synthesis can achieve identification accuracy exceeding 99 % for aircraft structural damage patterns (Wang et al., 2024).

3.4.4 Stakeholder Interviews and Document Analysis

Semi‑structured interviews will be conducted with three stakeholder groups:

· MRO engineers and inspectors (n = 6–8): To understand current inspection workflows, pain points, and attitudes toward AI‑augmented inspection.
· Industry managers (n = 3–5): To identify barriers to AI adoption (cost, skills, regulatory) and preferences for innovation support instruments.
· Policy makers and regulators (n = 3–5): To assess the current status of the DGAC drone decree, the operationalisation of the Al‑Jazari Institutes, and the availability of public funding for AI‑aerospace R&D.

Interviews will be recorded (with consent), transcribed and analysed using thematic analysis (Braun & Clarke, 2006). A semi‑structured interview protocol is provided in Appendix A.

Document analysis will be conducted on:

· The DGAC draft decree on civilian drones (to assess regulatory constraints and opportunities)
· The “Maroc IA 2030” strategy and related policy documents
· GIMAS annual reports and industry white papers
· International best‑practice documents (e.g., A*STAR ARTC model, Enterprise Ireland Innovation Voucher guidelines)

3.5 AI Model Development: Hybrid CNN‑LSTM Architecture

3.5.1 Rationale for Hybrid Architecture

The technical core of this research is a hybrid CNN‑LSTM (Convolutional Neural Network – Long Short‑Term Memory) architecture for defect detection in aerospace components. This hybrid approach is justified by the complementary strengths of the two architectures:

· CNN layers extract spatial features from image‑based NDE data (e.g., optical images of fuselage surfaces, thermographic images), identifying patterns characteristic of porosity, delamination, corrosion or fatigue cracks.
· LSTM layers capture temporal patterns from signal‑based data (e.g., acoustic emission waveforms, vibration time series), tracking the evolution of structural deterioration over time—a critical capability for predictive maintenance applications.

The literature has demonstrated that hybrid CNN‑LSTM systems achieve up to 98 % accuracy in pattern recognition for complex damage detection, significantly outperforming individual AI techniques (Donatus, 2025). Furthermore, when applied to ultrasonic guided wave‑based damage localisation, TL combined with CNNs has been shown to enable effective damage diagnosis even when labelled data are scarce (Lomazzi et al., 2024).

3.5.2 Proposed Architecture

The proposed CNN‑LSTM architecture consists of the following layers (from input to output):

Layer Type Parameters Output Shape
Input (image) 224 × 224 × 3 (RGB) 224 × 224 × 3
Conv2D + ReLU 64 filters, 3 × 3 kernel 224 × 224 × 64
MaxPooling2D 2 × 2 pool 112 × 112 × 64
Conv2D + ReLU 128 filters, 3 × 3 kernel 112 × 112 × 128
MaxPooling2D 2 × 2 pool 56 × 56 × 128
Conv2D + ReLU 256 filters, 3 × 3 kernel 56 × 56 × 256
MaxPooling2D 2 × 2 pool 28 × 28 × 256
Flatten — 200,704
Dense + ReLU 512 units 512
Reshape (sequence length) (32, 16)
LSTM 128 units, return sequences = True (32, 128)
LSTM 64 units 64
Dense + Sigmoid 3 units (defect classes) 3

The output layer uses a sigmoid activation for multi‑label classification (an image may contain multiple defect types). The model will be trained using the Adam optimiser with a learning rate of 0.001 and binary cross‑entropy loss.

3.5.3 Transfer Learning Strategy

To address the limited availability of labelled aerospace defect data in Morocco, a two‑stage transfer learning strategy will be employed:

Stage 1: Pre‑training on public datasets. A base CNN (MobileNetV3‑Small or EfficientNet‑B0) will be pre‑trained on ImageNet (for general feature extraction) and then fine‑tuned on the combined public defect datasets (GDXray, AVI, DAGM). This stage produces a model capable of detecting generic surface anomalies.

Stage 2: Domain adaptation to Moroccan MRO context. The pre‑trained model will be fine‑tuned using a small set of real‑world images (n = 200–300) collected from the partner facility, combined with the synthetic dataset (n = 5,000). Domain adaptation techniques—specifically, feature alignment and fine‑tuning with a low learning rate (1e‑5) —will be used to adapt the model to the specific lighting, surface conditions and defect morphologies present in the Midparc environment.

This approach is consistent with recent research demonstrating that transfer learning can be leveraged to adapt pre‑trained ML tools to new situations and tasks when few labelled data are available (Lomazzi et al., 2024). In the context of aeronautics composite materials, deep transfer learning models have achieved 96 % classification accuracy for inclusion defect detection (Gong et al., 2020).

3.5.4 Edge Deployment Optimisation

For the drone‑based or ground‑based prototype, the trained model must run on an edge device (e.g., NVIDIA Jetson Orin or Raspberry Pi with a Coral TPU) with limited computational resources. The following optimisation techniques will be applied:

· Model quantisation: Conversion of 32‑bit floating‑point weights to 8‑bit integers, reducing model size by approximately 75 % with minimal accuracy loss.
· Pruning: Removal of weights with near‑zero magnitude (threshold = 0.01 × maximum weight), reducing the number of parameters by up to 50 %.
· TensorRT optimisation: Deployment using NVIDIA TensorRT for accelerated inference on Jetson devices.

Target inference time: ≤ 100 ms per image at 30 fps, enabling real‑time inspection during drone flight.

3.6 Validation and Evaluation Metrics

3.6.1 Technical Performance Metrics

The AI model will be evaluated using the following metrics, calculated on a held‑out test set (20 % of the total dataset, stratified by defect type):

Metric Definition Target
Accuracy (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN) 95 %
Precision TP / (TP + FP) 90 %
Recall (Sensitivity) TP / (TP + FN) 90 %
F1‑Score 2 × (Precision × Recall) / (Precision + Recall) 0.92
Inference Time Time per image on edge device ≤ 100 ms

Where:

· TP = True Positive (defect correctly identified)
· TN = True Negative (non‑defect correctly identified)
· FP = False Positive (non‑defect incorrectly flagged as defect)
· FN = False Negative (defect missed)

3.6.2 Operational Performance Metrics

The operational impact of the prototype will be assessed through a controlled before‑after study at the partner facility:

1. Baseline period (Months 0–1) : All inspections are performed manually. Metrics are recorded for a minimum of 20 inspection events.
2. Deployment period (Months 6–9) : The prototype is deployed alongside manual inspections. The same metrics are recorded for a minimum of 20 inspection events using the prototype.
3. Comparative analysis: The following operational metrics are compared:
   · Inspection time reduction (%) = (Time_manual − Time_AI) / Time_manual × 100
   · Defect detection improvement (%) = (Defects_AI − Defects_manual) / Defects_manual × 100 (only for defects later confirmed by certified inspector)
   · False positive reduction (%) = (FP_rate_manual − FP_rate_AI) / FP_rate_manual × 100

3.7 Return on Investment (ROI) Calculation

3.7.1 Cost Model

The ROI analysis is calibrated to Moroccan labour costs and facility scales. The following cost categories are considered:

Labour costs:

· MRO inspector hourly wage (Morocco): €25 (approximately 250 MAD per hour)
· Number of inspectors per shift (baseline): 2
· Inspection time per aircraft (baseline manual): 4 hours
· Inspection time per aircraft (AI‑assisted): 1 hour (target)

Labour cost avoidance per inspection = (2 × 4 × €25) − (2 × 1 × €25) = €200 − €50 = €150 per aircraft

System costs:

· Hardware (drone or robotic arm, edge computer, cameras): €15,000–25,000
· Software development (PhD time, valued at €40,000 per year for 2 years): €80,000
· Training and integration: €10,000
· Total capital investment: €105,000–115,000

Recurring costs:

· Maintenance and updates (annual): €5,000
· Cloud compute for model retraining (annual): €2,000

3.7.2 Benefit Model

Annual labour savings for a facility inspecting 100 aircraft per year:

€150 × 100 = €15,000

Defect remediation savings: Assuming the AI system detects 30 % more early‑stage defects (converting €100,000 structural repairs into €5,000 early interventions), the annual saving is estimated at 0.3 × (100,000 − 5,000) × (20 defects per year) = €570,000.

Total annual benefit = €15,000 + €570,000 = €585,000

ROI calculation (3‑year horizon) :

Year Cash Flow (€) Cumulative
0 (investment) −110,000 −110,000
1 585,000 − 7,000 = 578,000 468,000
2 585,000 − 7,000 = 578,000 1,046,000
3 585,000 − 7,000 = 578,000 1,624,000

ROI = (Total benefits − Total costs) / Total costs = (1,624,000 − 110,000) / 110,000 = 14.8x over 3 years

This figure is considerably higher than the 3.4x ROI reported for European MRO facilities, reflecting the lower baseline labour costs in Morocco (which makes labour reduction less valuable) but the high cost of structural repairs (which makes defect detection more valuable). To present a conservative estimate, the research will report a range of 2–3x ROI in the final analysis, assuming more modest defect remediation savings (€50,000 per incident rather than €95,000).

The ROI model will be refined as primary data become available during Phase 3. A sensitivity analysis will be conducted for the following parameters:

· Labour cost (±20 %)
· Defect remediation saving (±50 %)
· Number of aircraft inspected per year (±50 %)

3.8 AI Innovation Voucher Feasibility Study

3.8.1 Research Design

The feasibility study for a sector‑specific AI Innovation Voucher scheme follows a formative evaluation design (Patton, 2010). The goal is not to evaluate an existing programme but to develop a blueprint for a future programme, grounded in primary stakeholder data and international best practice.

3.8.2 Data Collection

Primary data for the feasibility study will be collected through:

1. Semi‑structured interviews with innovation managers from 5–10 GIMAS SMEs (representing a range of sizes and subsectors). The interview protocol covers:
   · Current R&D expenditure on AI or digital technologies
   · Willingness to co‑finance an AI project (matching funds)
   · Preferred voucher value and project duration
   · Barriers to engaging with universities or research labs
2. Document analysis of existing innovation voucher programmes (UK Innovate UK, Enterprise Ireland, Slovak Creative Vouchers) to extract design parameters (voucher value, co‑financing requirement, eligibility criteria, evaluation methods).

3.8.3 Proposed Voucher Design

Based on the international literature and preliminary stakeholder input, the following design parameters are proposed for the feasibility study:

Parameter Proposed Value Justification
Voucher value €20,000 Sufficient for a focused AI feasibility study or small‑scale prototype; aligns with Enterprise Ireland and BridgeAI models
Co‑financing 50 % (SME contributes €10,000) Reduces risk of inefficient use of funds; ensures SME commitment
Eligible activities Technical feasibility study, prototype development, data acquisition, model training Covers the full AI adoption pipeline
Knowledge providers UM6P, UIR, AEROSUP, Al‑Jazari Institute Aligns with the “Maroc IA 2030” strategy
Evaluation method Randomised controlled trial (RCT) with treatment and control groups, plus qualitative follow‑up RCTs have been shown to reveal both short‑term and longer‑term impacts that other methods miss (Nesta, 2013)

The feasibility study will be delivered as a stand‑alone report (20–30 pages) containing:

