3.9 Skills Passport Pilot

3.9.1 Target Cohort and Curriculum

A pilot Skills Passport programme will be delivered to 20–30 technicians recruited from the Institut des Métiers de l’Aéronautique (IMA) and AEROSUP. The programme comprises six micro‑credential modules, each requiring 20–30 hours of study (blended learning: online theory + hands‑on lab sessions):

Module Content Delivery Method
1 Introduction to AI and computer vision for aerospace Online
2 Non‑destructive evaluation techniques (ultrasonic, thermographic, visual) Lab (AMC Labs)
3 Autonomous drone operation for inspection Lab (simulator + controlled flights)
4 Data annotation and model training fundamentals Online + hands‑on
5 Interpreting AI outputs for maintenance decisions Case‑based (industry scenarios)
6 Capstone project: AI‑assisted inspection of a real component On‑site (partner facility)

3.9.2 Evaluation

The pilot will be evaluated using a pre‑test/post‑test design:

· Pre‑test: A 60‑minute assessment of knowledge of NDE methods and AI fundamentals (scored 0–100).
· Post‑test: The same assessment administered upon completion of the six modules.
· Skills demonstration: A practical assessment in which the technician performs an AI‑assisted inspection and interprets the outputs.

Success criteria:

· Completion rate ≥ 80 %
· Average improvement from pre‑test to post‑test ≥ 30 percentage points
· Practical assessment pass rate ≥ 90 %
· Employer satisfaction (survey of hiring managers) ≥ 4.0/5.0

The Skills Passport pilot will be documented in a separate report, including the curriculum, assessment instruments, and recommendations for scaling to a national programme under the “Maroc IA 2030” framework.

3.10 Contingency Plan: Drone Regulation

3.10.1 Regulatory Uncertainty

As documented in Chapter 2, civilian drone operations for commercial MRO remain heavily restricted in Morocco as of mid‑2026. The draft decree prepared by the DGAC has not yet been gazetted, and there is no public evidence of imminent liberalisation. This uncertainty constitutes a critical risk to the research plan.

3.10.2 Contingency Trigger and Pivot

If the DGAC has not granted explicit authorisation for drone flights (indoor or outdoor) at the partner facility by Month 9 (end of Phase 1), the research will pivot from a flying drone prototype to a ground‑based autonomous system. The pivot decision will be made by the supervisory committee in consultation with the DGAC.

3.10.3 Ground‑Based Alternatives

Two ground‑based alternatives have been designed as drop‑in replacements:

Option A: Robotic arm with mobile base. A 6‑degree‑of‑freedom robotic arm (e.g., Dobot CR5 or UR10e) mounted on an automated guided vehicle (AGV) will navigate around stationary components (landing gear struts, composite panels) and perform close‑up visual and thermal inspection. The AI model (CNN‑LSTM) remains unchanged; only the physical platform changes.

Option B: Fixed multi‑camera array. A conveyor or turntable system will move components through a fixed array of high‑resolution cameras and thermal sensors. This option is suitable for smaller components (brackets, fasteners) and can be housed entirely indoors.

Both alternatives require no regulatory approval beyond standard industrial safety clearances. The hardware costs (€15,000–25,000) are comparable to the drone option, and the development timeline remains unchanged (the pivoted prototype will be delivered by Month 18).

The contingency plan is explicitly budgeted in Phase 2 equipment costs. No additional funding is required.

