Chapter 5: Proposed Technical Architecture and Conceptual Design

5.1 Introduction

This chapter presents a conceptual technical architecture for an AI‑driven autonomous inspection system applicable to Moroccan aerospace MRO. No physical prototype has been built, and no experimental results are reported. Instead, the chapter synthesises existing literature on computer vision, hybrid neural networks, edge AI, and autonomous robotics to propose a theoretically sound design that could be implemented in future research or industrial projects.

5.2 Proposed Autonomous Inspection Modalities

Based on a review of commercial and academic systems (Donecle, AAR, EasyJet’s predictive maintenance, and peer‑reviewed studies on drone‑based NDE), two complementary modalities are identified as theoretically suitable for the Moroccan context:

1. Aerial drone‑based exterior fuselage inspection: An autonomous UAV equipped with high‑resolution RGB and thermal cameras, flying a pre‑programmed trajectory around a stationary aircraft. This modality is contingent on regulatory approval (see Chapter 4).
2. Ground‑based robotic arm inspection: A 6‑degree‑of‑freedom collaborative robot mounted on a mobile base, designed for close‑up inspection of landing gear components, composite panels, or other high‑value parts. This modality is independent of drone regulation and can be deployed indoors.

Both modalities share a common AI pipeline, described below.

5.3 Proposed AI Pipeline Architecture

5.3.1 Data Acquisition Layer

· Sensors: RGB camera (5 MP+), thermal camera (160 × 120 minimum), optional laser profilometer for 3D topography.
· Acquisition conditions: Controlled lighting (300–800 lux), standoff distance 0.3–0.5 m.
· Data rate: 1–2 images per second per sensor.

5.3.2 Proposed Hybrid CNN‑LSTM Model

Drawing on the literature reviewed in Chapter 2, a hybrid architecture is proposed that combines spatial feature extraction (CNN) with temporal sequence modelling (LSTM). The architecture is as follows (conceptual):

Layer Type Parameters Output
Input Image (224×224×3) — 224×224×3
Backbone EfficientNet‑B0 (pre‑trained on ImageNet) 4.0M parameters 7×7×1280 feature map
Pooling Global average pooling — 1280‑dim vector
Reshape Sequence formation (32 timesteps) — (32, 40)
LSTM 1 128 units, return sequences=True 86,528 parameters (32, 128)
LSTM 2 64 units 49,408 parameters 64
Dense 3 units (defect classes), sigmoid 195 parameters 3

The model is designed for multi‑label classification (corrosion, crack, lightning‑strike damage). Transfer learning from ImageNet is proposed to reduce data requirements, as documented in numerous studies on defect detection with limited labelled data.

5.3.3 Training Data Strategy (Theoretical)

Given the absence of a large, labelled Moroccan aerospace defect dataset, a theoretical data strategy is proposed:

· Transfer learning: Pre‑train on public datasets (GDXray, DAGM 2007, Aircraft Visual Inspection Dataset) to learn generic defect features.
· Synthetic data generation: Use a physics‑based rendering engine (e.g., Blender Cycles) to create labelled synthetic images of aircraft panels with injected defects under varying lighting and angles. This approach has been validated in the literature (e.g., for aero‑engine blade inspection).
· Domain adaptation: Fine‑tune the pre‑trained model using a small set of real images (e.g., 200–300) collected from a partner facility, employing feature alignment techniques to adapt to local conditions (lighting, surface finish).

This strategy is theoretically sound and has been demonstrated in multiple peer‑reviewed studies; it is proposed as the methodological blueprint for future empirical work.

5.3.4 Edge Deployment Architecture

For real‑time inference, the proposed model would be deployed on an edge AI device such as the NVIDIA Jetson Orin NX (up to 157 TOPS). Optimisation techniques proposed include:

· Quantisation: Convert weights from FP32 to FP16 or INT8, reducing model size and latency.
· Pruning: Remove near‑zero weight channels (threshold = 0.01 × max weight).
· TensorRT acceleration: Use NVIDIA’s inference optimisation library.

Theoretical target inference time: ≤ 100 ms per image, enabling real‑time inspection during drone or robotic movement.

5.4 Theoretical ROI Model (Literature‑Based)

Based on industry reports (Donecle, AAR, easyJet) and academic studies on predictive maintenance ROI, a theoretical ROI model is constructed for a mid‑sized Moroccan MRO facility.

Assumptions (drawn from literature) :

· Baseline manual inspection: 4 hours, 2 inspectors, labour cost €25/hour.
· AI‑assisted inspection: 1 hour, 1 inspector (supervisory role).
· Defect remediation: AI detects 30 % more early‑stage defects, converting €100,000 structural repairs into €5,000 early interventions.

Theoretical annual benefit (for a facility inspecting 100 aircraft per year):

Component Calculation Amount (€)
Labour saving (2×4×25) − (1×1×25) = 200−25 = 175 per aircraft × 100 17,500
Defect remediation saving 0.3 × (100,000−5,000) × (20 defects/year) 570,000
Total annual benefit  587,500

Theoretical investment cost (one‑time):

Component Cost (€)
Hardware (drone or robotic arm, sensors, edge computer) 20,000
Software development (PhD time valued at 40,000/year for 2 years) 80,000
Training and integration 10,000
Total investment 110,000

Theoretical ROI over 3 years (ignoring discounting for simplicity):

(587,500 × 3 − 110,000) / 110,000 = 15.0x

A conservative range of 2–3x is proposed, given uncertainties in defect remediation savings and adoption rates. This ROI model is presented as a hypothesis to be tested in future empirical research.

