The proposed architecture is theoretically comparable to state‑of‑the‑art commercial systems, with the added novelty of being specifically adapted to Moroccan industrial constraints (cost sensitivity, limited labelled data, regulatory uncertainty) through the proposed transfer learning and synthetic data strategies.

5.6 Summary of Proposed Technical Contributions

This chapter has presented a conceptual design for an AI‑driven autonomous inspection system tailored to the Moroccan aerospace MRO context. The key theoretical contributions are:

1. A hybrid CNN‑LSTM architecture that leverages transfer learning to address data scarcity.
2. A synthetic data generation pipeline using physics‑based rendering to augment limited real datasets.
3. An edge deployment strategy enabling real‑time inference on cost‑effective hardware (e.g., Jetson Orin).
4. A literature‑based ROI model calibrated to Moroccan labour costs, projecting a 2–15x return on investment over three years.

No empirical validation has been conducted. The proposed architecture is intended as a blueprint for future research, industrial pilots, or policy‑funded demonstration projects under the “Maroc IA 2030” framework.

Chapter 6: Discussion and Policy Implications

6.1 Introduction

This chapter synthesises the key theoretical findings of the research, interprets their significance within the broader Moroccan industrial transformation agenda, and derives actionable policy implications. Unlike empirical studies, this chapter does not report experimental results but rather discusses the strategic implications of the proposed AI‑driven autonomous inspection framework in light of existing literature, policy documents, and comparative case studies. The chapter is organised into five sections: an interpretation of the theoretical findings relative to the research questions; a discussion of the barriers and enablers for AI adoption in the Moroccan aerospace MRO context; the policy implications structured around the three‑pillar framework; an analysis of the transferability of the proposed model to other sectors; and a reflection on the limitations of this theoretical research.

6.2 Interpretation of Theoretical Findings

6.2.1 Addressing the Research Questions

RQ1 (Technical feasibility) : The theoretical design of the hybrid CNN‑LSTM architecture presented in Chapter 5, combined with the proposed transfer learning and synthetic data generation strategy, suggests that a defect detection accuracy exceeding 95 % is theoretically achievable under Moroccan MRO conditions. This confidence is grounded in the literature: hybrid CNN‑LSTM systems have been demonstrated to achieve up to 98 % accuracy in pattern recognition for complex damage detection, and deep transfer learning models have achieved 96 % classification accuracy for inclusion defect detection in aeronautics composite materials. The synthetic data generation approach addresses the challenge of limited labelled data, which the literature identifies as a critical barrier to AI adoption in emerging markets.

RQ2 (Operational ROI) : The theoretical ROI model calibrated to Moroccan labour costs (€25/hour) projects a range of 2–15x return on investment over three years, with a conservative estimate of 2–3x. This range is consistent with industry benchmarks: AI‑based predictive maintenance systems have been shown to reduce downtime by 50 % and cut operational expenses. For a mid‑sized MRO facility, the projected annual labour saving of €17,500 and defect remediation saving of €570,000 appear plausible, though the latter is highly sensitive to the actual frequency of high‑cost structural repairs—a parameter that would require empirical validation.

RQ3 (Institutional transfer) : The triple helix model (university‑industry‑government) has been successfully applied in aviation innovation contexts, as demonstrated by the UAE‑Sweden partnership study. The proposed Integrated Research Unit (IRU) draws on this validated framework. The literature on innovation vouchers in Africa—such as the IDRC‑funded project developing a scalable R&D Voucher Toolkit for multiple African countries—provides empirical precedent for the feasibility of the proposed voucher scheme. The Skills Passport concept is validated by international micro‑credential programmes in aerospace manufacturing, including competency‑based training to address skills shortages within the advanced manufacturing and aerospace sector.

6.2.2 Strategic Alignment with National Policy

The proposed framework aligns closely with the “Maroc IA 2030” strategy launched in January 2026, which aims to contribute $10 billion to national GDP and create 50,000 direct and indirect AI‑related jobs by 2030. The strategy is built on five pillars: technological sovereignty, citizen trust, massive skills development, endogenous innovation, and territorial equity. The three‑pillar framework proposed in this research directly supports each of these pillars: the IRU contributes to technological sovereignty by building local R&D capacity; the Skills Passport addresses the massive skills development target of training 200,000 graduates in AI skills; and the Innovation Voucher scheme promotes endogenous innovation among SMEs.

The territorial deployment of the AI strategy has commenced with the inauguration of the Al‑Jazari Institute for Industry X.0 in Fès, which focuses on IoT, advanced robotics, production data analytics, and predictive maintenance. This institutional infrastructure provides a ready‑made platform for the IRU joint lab concept proposed in this research.

6.3 Barriers and Enablers for AI Adoption in Moroccan Aerospace MRO

6.3.1 Identified Barriers

Regulatory uncertainty: As documented in Chapter 4, civilian drone operations remain heavily restricted in Morocco. While the DGAC has developed a draft decree establishing a regulatory framework for drone design, production, maintenance, and operation, the decree has not yet been gazetted. Until then, the general prohibition on drone importation, possession, and use remains in force. This uncertainty constitutes a significant barrier to the deployment of drone‑based autonomous inspection systems, though the ground‑based contingency proposed in this research mitigates this risk.

Skills and talent gap: Moroccan enterprises recognise that AI adoption is no longer optional but a necessity for modernising processes and remaining competitive. However, a parliamentary report on AI in Morocco has identified the lack of an appropriate legislative framework and insufficient skills development as major challenges. While Morocco exceeds global averages in AI adoption among African economies, it remains relatively low in R&D intensity (ranked 42nd globally) and ICT infrastructure (88th).

Fragmented data and legacy systems: The MRO industry globally faces challenges including fragmented data, unstructured maintenance histories, and regulatory compliance requirements. These challenges are amplified in the Moroccan context, where digital transformation is still underway.

Adoption caution: The global MRO industry is adopting AI slowly, with aviation’s safety‑critical nature meaning maintenance shops move forward cautiously. Only 34 % of surveyed MRO professionals report already using AI, while 62 % are interested but just starting to explore its potential. This caution is justified and should inform the phased approach recommended in this research.

6.3.2 Enabling Factors

Sovereign digital infrastructure: The UM6P “Toubkal” supercomputer—Africa’s most powerful—provides the computational capacity necessary for training large‑scale AI models without reliance on international cloud providers. The planned 500 MW “Dakhla AI Battery” green data centre will further enhance Morocco’s sovereign compute capacity.

Growing startup and VC ecosystem: In 2024, Moroccan startups raised nearly $95 million in venture capital across 40 deals, almost tripling the $33 million recorded the previous year. Local VCs, led by UM6P Ventures and Al Mada Ventures, accounted for roughly 70 % of all funding deployed in 2024, reducing foreign capital dependency. The government’s Startup Venture Building programme, backed by a MAD 700 million fund, provides multi‑stage financing and a monthly living allowance for founders, with a target of creating 1,000 startups by 2026 and 3,000 by 2030.

Existing Industry 4.0 initiatives: GIMAS has launched the three‑phase “Morocco Aeronautics 4.0” programme to support the industry of the future. This demonstrates sectoral awareness of the need for digital transformation and provides a potential vehicle for the proposed framework.

Local drone manufacturing capability: Moroccan company AeroDrive Engineering Service has successfully tested the “Atlas” drone, which features AI‑powered image and video collection capabilities and a low cost of approximately $2,000. This indicates that local technical capacity for drone development already exists, providing a foundation for the proposed autonomous inspection systems.

6.4 Policy Implications

6.4.1 Pillar 1: Integrated Research Unit (IRU) — Institutionalising Triple Helix Collaboration

The first policy implication is the need to institutionalise the IRU model within the Al‑Jazari Institute network. The Al‑Jazari Institute for Industry X.0 in Fès is designed to accompany the transition of Moroccan enterprises towards Industry 4.0, with solutions covering IoT, advanced robotics, production data analytics, and predictive maintenance. The IRU model proposed in this research would operationalise this mandate by creating a physical co‑location space where PhD researchers, post‑doctoral fellows, and industry engineers work side‑by‑side on real‑time manufacturing challenges.

Policy recommendation: The Ministry of Digital Transition should issue a call for proposals to establish a pilot IRU within the Casablanca Aerospace City, with funding of MAD 2–3 million over three years, co‑financed by GIMAS member firms. The IRU should be governed by a steering committee comprising university representatives (UM6P, UIR), industry representatives (GIMAS), and government representatives (Ministry of Industry, DGAC).

6.4.2 Pillar 2: AI Innovation Voucher — De‑risking SME Engagement

The second policy implication concerns the design and implementation of a sector‑specific AI Innovation Voucher scheme. International evidence demonstrates that innovation vouchers are effective in building links between SMEs and public knowledge providers. The IDRC‑funded project “Catalyzing SME Growth through Scalable R&D Impact Vouchers in Africa” is currently developing a scalable, open‑access R&D Voucher Toolkit suitable for replication by innovation hubs, research councils, and government ministries. This project operates in Kenya, Uganda, Ethiopia, Tanzania, South Africa, Burkina Faso, and Senegal—but not yet Morocco.

Policy recommendation: The Ministry of Digital Transition should partner with GIMAS and the Al‑Jazari Institute network to launch a pilot AI Innovation Voucher scheme for aerospace SMEs, with the following design parameters:

· Voucher value: MAD 200,000 (approximately €20,000)
· Co‑financing: 50 % SME contribution
· Eligible activities: Technical feasibility studies, prototype development, data acquisition, model training
· Knowledge providers: UM6P, UIR, AEROSUP, Al‑Jazari Institutes
· Evaluation: Randomised controlled trial with treatment and control groups, following the IDRC methodology

The scheme should be designed to be scalable to other sectors (automotive, phosphate, renewables) after the pilot phase.

6.4.3 Pillar 3: Skills Passport — Building the AI‑Augmented Workforce

The third policy implication concerns the development of a national Skills Passport for AI‑augmented inspection technicians. The “Maroc IA 2030” strategy explicitly targets the training of 200,000 graduates in AI skills. The Digital Morocco 2030 strategy aims to add MAD 100 billion to GDP, create 240,000 digital sector jobs, and double the number of digital graduates by 2027. These ambitious targets require structured, competency‑based training pathways.

International precedent exists in the aerospace sector: competency‑based training programmes addressing skills shortages within the advanced manufacturing and aerospace sector, with participants earning industry digital badges to improve marketability. The European Union’s DigComp framework provides a competence model for micro‑credentials that can be adapted to the Moroccan context.

Policy recommendation: The Ministry of Digital Transition, in collaboration with the Ministry of Industry and the Institut des Métiers de l’Aéronautique (IMA), should develop a national Skills Passport for AI‑augmented aerospace inspection. The passport should comprise six stackable micro‑credential modules, with assessment based on both theoretical knowledge and practical demonstration. A pilot cohort of 50 technicians should be trained within 12 months, with a target 20 % salary premium for certified holders.

6.4.4 Regulatory Sandbox — Accelerating Drone Deployment

Given the continued regulatory uncertainty surrounding civilian drones, the fourth policy implication is the establishment of a formal regulatory sandbox for autonomous inspection systems. The DGAC has developed a draft decree that will establish rules and procedures for drone design, production, maintenance, and operation. However, until the decree is gazetted, commercial MRO drone operations remain effectively impossible.

Policy recommendation: The DGAC should establish a formal regulatory sandbox, modelled on similar initiatives in the European Union and Singapore, to authorise controlled indoor drone flights within designated areas of the Casablanca Aerospace City. The sandbox should include:

· Flights conducted below 5 metres altitude within a netted enclosure
· Tethered drones with ground power and data connection
· Real‑time remote monitoring by a DGAC‑approved safety officer
· Data collection to inform the final regulatory framework

This sandbox would serve as a “living laboratory” for the regulatory framework, generating evidence to support the final decree while enabling innovation to proceed without waiting for full legislation.

6.4.5 Financing and Sustainability

The final policy implication concerns financing mechanisms for sustained AI‑aerospace R&D. The government’s Startup Venture Building programme, backed by a MAD 700 million fund, provides end‑to‑end support for startups through multi‑stage financing and strategic partnerships with local and international ecosystem operators. However, this programme is focused on startups rather than established SMEs or joint research infrastructure.

Policy recommendation: The Ministry of Finance should allocate a specific allocation within the Startup Venture Building programme for “Industry 4.0 Transition Vouchers” targeting established manufacturing SMEs, not only startups. Additionally, the government should explore blended finance mechanisms that combine public, private, and philanthropic resources to sustain the IRU model beyond the pilot phase, following the approach recommended by the IDRC voucher project.

6.5 Transferability to Other Sectors

While this research focuses on aerospace MRO, the proposed three‑pillar framework is theoretically transferable to other Moroccan industrial sectors that share similar characteristics: automotive, phosphate processing, and renewable energy manufacturing.

Automotive: Morocco’s automotive sector is larger than aerospace in employment terms and faces similar challenges in quality control, predictive maintenance, and Industry 4.0 adoption. The IRU model could be replicated within the Tangier Automotive City, and the AI Innovation Voucher scheme could be extended to automotive SMEs.

Phosphate: OCP Group, Morocco’s phosphate giant, has already invested heavily in digital transformation and AI through UM6P. The IRU model could be adapted for predictive maintenance of mining and processing equipment.

Renewable energy: With Morocco’s target of 52 % renewable energy by 2030, AI‑driven predictive maintenance for wind turbines and solar panels is a high‑priority application. The Skills Passport could be adapted for renewable energy technicians.

The common success factor across all sectors is the presence of a strong industry association (GIMAS for aerospace, AMICA for automotive, OCP for phosphate) capable of coordinating the triple helix collaboration. The policy implication is that the government should adopt the IRU and Innovation Voucher models as horizontal instruments applicable across all manufacturing sectors, not only aerospace.

6.6 Limitations of the Theoretical Research

This research has several limitations that must be acknowledged.

Absence of empirical validation: As a purely theoretical study, the proposed technical architecture has not been validated in a live industrial setting. The defect detection accuracy target of >95 % and the inspection time reduction target of 60–80 % are derived from literature and industry reports, not from Moroccan‑specific empirical data. Future research should conduct a pilot deployment to validate these assumptions.

Data availability constraints: The ROI model relies on assumptions about defect remediation savings that may not hold in the Moroccan MRO context. The actual frequency of high‑cost structural repairs, the effectiveness of early detection, and the willingness of insurers and regulators to accept AI‑generated inspection reports are all unknown parameters that would require empirical investigation.

Regulatory evolution uncertainty: The regulatory landscape for drones and AI in Morocco is evolving. The draft DGAC decree may be gazetted during the course of this research, or it may be delayed further. The regulatory sandbox proposal is theoretical and would require negotiation with multiple government agencies.

Sectoral specificity: The findings are derived from the aerospace MRO context and may not transfer directly to other sectors without adaptation. Each sector has its own regulatory framework, skills base, and industry structure.

Single‑country focus: The research focuses exclusively on Morocco. While comparative insights from Singapore, Montreal, and Toulouse are incorporated, the transferability of the findings to other African or emerging economies would require further research.

6.7 Summary

This chapter has interpreted the theoretical findings of the research, identified the key barriers and enablers for AI adoption in Moroccan aerospace MRO, and derived five actionable policy recommendations: institutionalising the IRU model within the Al‑Jazari Institute network; launching a pilot AI Innovation Voucher scheme for aerospace SMEs; developing a national Skills Passport for AI‑augmented inspection technicians; establishing a formal regulatory sandbox for autonomous inspection systems; and allocating specific financing mechanisms within the Startup Venture Building programme for Industry 4.0 transition. The proposed framework is transferable to other Moroccan industrial sectors, including automotive, phosphate, and renewable energy. The limitations of this theoretical research—notably the absence of empirical validation—are acknowledged and will inform the future research agenda presented in Chapter 7.

Chapter 7: Conclusion and Future Research

7.1 Introduction

This concluding chapter synthesises the key contributions of the research, reflects on the theoretical and policy implications, and outlines a forward‑looking agenda for future research. The chapter is organised into four sections: a summary of the research and its key findings; the theoretical, policy, and methodological contributions; a future research agenda comprising seven priority directions; and final concluding remarks.

7.2 Summary of the Research

This PhD research has addressed the structural gap between industrial maturity and high‑value innovation in the Moroccan aerospace sector by proposing a theoretically grounded, PhD‑executable roadmap for AI‑driven autonomous systems in aerospace MRO. The research was motivated by three concurrent developments: the “Maroc IA 2030” national AI strategy (launched January 2026), the growing industrial concentration of aerospace activity in the Casablanca Aerospace City (approximately 150 companies, €2.5 billion annual revenue, 23,000–26,000 workers), and the emerging but uncertain regulatory framework for civilian drones.

The research was structured around three research questions addressing technical feasibility, operational ROI, and institutional transfer. Chapter 2 provided a systematic literature review of the Moroccan aerospace ecosystem, national AI strategies, global cluster models (Toulouse, Montreal, Singapore), AI applications in MRO, and innovation policy instruments (innovation vouchers, joint labs, skills passports). Chapter 3 presented the methodology, grounded in a pragmatist paradigm and design science research approach, with a mixed‑methods design combining quantitative and qualitative elements.

Chapters 4 and 5 established the theoretical baseline and proposed technical architecture. Chapter 4 synthesised existing literature and policy documents to define the current industrial baseline and co‑design a three‑pillar strategic framework: (1) Integrated Research Unit (IRU) joint lab; (2) AI Innovation Voucher scheme; and (3) AI‑Augmented Skills Passport. Chapter 5 presented a conceptual technical architecture for an AI‑driven autonomous inspection system, including a hybrid CNN‑LSTM model, transfer learning and synthetic data generation strategy, edge deployment optimisation, and a literature‑based ROI model calibrated to Moroccan labour costs.

Chapter 6 interpreted the theoretical findings, identified barriers and enablers for AI adoption, derived policy implications, and discussed transferability to other sectors. The present chapter concludes the research and outlines future directions.

7.3 Contributions of the Research

7.3.1 Theoretical Contributions

Contribution 1: A synthesised framework for AI‑aerospace innovation in an emerging economy. This research integrates insights from the triple helix model of innovation (university‑industry‑government), the Singaporean A*STAR joint lab model, the Montreal decentralised cluster model, and the Moroccan national AI strategy into a coherent three‑pillar framework. This synthesis is novel in the literature on African aerospace development, which has previously focused on descriptive cluster analysis rather than prescriptive innovation frameworks.

Contribution 2: A theoretically grounded technical architecture adapted to resource constraints. The proposed hybrid CNN‑LSTM architecture, combined with transfer learning from public datasets and synthetic data generation, addresses the specific constraint of limited labelled defect data—a common challenge in emerging economies. The theoretical ROI model calibrated to Moroccan labour costs provides a benchmark for future empirical validation.

Contribution 3: An integrated policy instrument design. Unlike previous studies that treat joint labs, innovation vouchers, and skills passports in isolation, this research integrates them into a mutually reinforcing system. The IRU provides the institutional platform for R&D; the Innovation Voucher provides the financing mechanism for SME engagement; and the Skills Passport provides the talent pipeline. This integrated design is a novel contribution to the innovation policy literature.

7.3.2 Policy Contributions

Contribution 4: Actionable policy recommendations for “Maroc IA 2030” implementation. The research provides five concrete policy recommendations that directly operationalise the national AI strategy: the IRU pilot within the Al‑Jazari Institute network; the AI Innovation Voucher scheme for aerospace SMEs; the national Skills Passport for AI‑augmented inspection technicians; the regulatory sandbox for autonomous inspection systems; and targeted financing mechanisms for Industry 4.0 transition. These recommendations are grounded in international best practice and adapted to the Moroccan institutional context.

Contribution 5: A regulatory sandbox proposal to accelerate drone deployment. Recognising that the DGAC draft decree has not yet been gazetted, the research proposes a formal regulatory sandbox as a pragmatic interim solution. This proposal, modelled on European and Singaporean precedents, provides a pathway for innovation to proceed while the full regulatory framework is finalised.

Contribution 6: A transferable framework for other Moroccan industrial sectors. The three‑pillar framework is designed to be horizontally transferable to automotive, phosphate processing, and renewable energy manufacturing. This scalability multiplies the policy impact of the research beyond the aerospace sector.

7.3.3 Methodological Contributions

Contribution 7: A design science research approach applied to African aerospace innovation. The application of design science research (DSR) to the problem of AI‑aerospace innovation in an African context is novel. DSR is well‑suited to problems where the goal is not merely to describe or predict but to intervene and create—a perfect fit for the prescriptive ambitions of this research.

Contribution 8: A theoretical baseline for future empirical validation. By establishing a comprehensive theoretical baseline of inspection times, defect detection rates, and ROI assumptions derived from literature, this research provides a benchmark against which future empirical studies can be compared. This is a valuable contribution to the evidence base for AI adoption in African manufacturing.

7.4 Future Research Agenda

The following seven priority directions for future research are identified, ranging from short‑term empirical validation to long‑term comparative and theoretical extensions.

7.4.1 Empirical Validation of the Proposed Technical Architecture

Priority 1: Pilot deployment of the ground‑based inspection system. The highest priority for future research is a pilot deployment of the proposed ground‑based autonomous inspection system within a live MRO facility in the Casablanca Aerospace City. This would involve:

· Collecting baseline inspection time and defect detection data (minimum 20 inspection events)
· Deploying the prototype for 6–12 months
· Measuring actual detection accuracy, inspection time reduction, and ROI
· Validating or refining the theoretical ROI model with empirical data

Research question: To what extent do the theoretical performance targets (95 % accuracy, 60–80 % time reduction) hold under real‑world Moroccan MRO conditions?

7.4.2 Dataset Development for Aerospace Defect Detection

Priority 2: Creation of a Moroccan aerospace defect dataset. A major barrier to AI adoption in Moroccan aerospace is the absence of a labelled, representative dataset of surface anomalies on aircraft operated in Moroccan conditions. Future research should:

· Partner with GIMAS member firms to collect and annotate images of corrosion, cracks, and lightning‑strike damage
· Establish data governance protocols that respect commercial confidentiality while enabling research access
· Release an anonymised benchmark dataset for the research community

Research question: What is the minimum dataset size required to achieve reliable defect detection under Moroccan MRO conditions, and what annotation protocols are most efficient?

7.4.3 Comparative Analysis of AI Adoption Across Sectors

Priority 3: Cross‑sectoral comparison of AI adoption barriers and enablers. The three‑pillar framework proposed in this research is theoretically transferable to automotive, phosphate, and renewable energy manufacturing. Future research should conduct comparative case studies to identify:

· Sector‑specific barriers (e.g., regulatory, technical, skills)
· Adaptations required to the IRU, voucher, and skills passport models
· Commonalities that enable a horizontal policy instrument

Research question: How do the barriers and enablers for AI adoption in aerospace MRO compare with those in automotive manufacturing, phosphate processing, and renewable energy?

7.4.4 Evaluation of Innovation Voucher Effectiveness

Priority 4: Impact evaluation of the AI Innovation Voucher scheme. If the proposed voucher scheme is implemented, a rigorous impact evaluation should be conducted, preferably using a randomised controlled trial design with treatment and control groups. The evaluation should measure:

· Changes in SME R&D expenditure and patenting activity
· Adoption of AI technologies and subsequent productivity gains
· Sustainability of university‑industry collaborations beyond the voucher period

Research question: Does the AI Innovation Voucher scheme cause a measurable increase in AI adoption and innovation output among treated SMEs compared to a control group?

7.4.5 Longitudinal Study of Skills Passport Outcomes

Priority 5: Tracking the career outcomes of Skills Passport holders. If the proposed Skills Passport is piloted, a longitudinal study should track certified technicians over 2–5 years to measure:

· Employment rates and salary progression compared to non‑certified peers
· Employer satisfaction and perceived value of the credential
· Retention of AI‑augmented inspection skills over time

Research question: What is the long‑term impact of Skills Passport certification on technician employability, salary, and career progression in the Moroccan aerospace sector?

7.4.6 Regulatory Sandbox Evaluation

Priority 6: Assessment of the regulatory sandbox as a policy instrument. If the proposed regulatory sandbox is established, future research should evaluate its effectiveness in:

· Accelerating the deployment of autonomous inspection systems
· Generating evidence to inform the final DGAC regulatory framework
· Balancing innovation with safety and security requirements

Research question: Under what conditions does a regulatory sandbox for autonomous inspection systems produce net benefits for innovation, safety, and regulatory learning?

7.4.7 Comparative International Analysis

Priority 7: Extension to other African aerospace clusters. Morocco is not the only African country developing aerospace capabilities. South Africa (Aerosud, Denel), Ethiopia (Ethiopian Airlines MRO), and Tunisia (Aéronautique cluster) have emerging aerospace sectors facing similar AI adoption challenges. Comparative research across these clusters would:

· Identify context‑specific factors affecting AI adoption
· Develop a contingency framework for transferring the three‑pillar model
· Contribute to a pan‑African evidence base for Industry 4.0 policy

Research question: How do the barriers and enablers for AI adoption in Moroccan aerospace compare with those in South Africa, Ethiopia, and Tunisia, and what adaptations to the three‑pillar framework are required in each context?

7.5 Concluding Remarks

The Moroccan aerospace sector stands at a strategic inflection point. It has successfully built a world‑class manufacturing and assembly hub, attracting major OEMs including Airbus, Boeing, and Safran. However, the transition from subcontractor to co‑innovator requires deliberate, sustained investment in R&D infrastructure, talent development, and policy instruments that de‑risk AI adoption for SMEs.

This research has proposed a theoretically grounded, PhD‑executable roadmap for AI‑driven autonomous systems in aerospace MRO, structured around three mutually reinforcing pillars: an Integrated Research Unit (IRU) joint lab modelled on Singapore’s A*STAR; an AI Innovation Voucher scheme to de‑risk SME engagement; and an AI‑Augmented Skills Passport to build the future workforce. The research has also proposed a regulatory sandbox to accelerate drone deployment and has identified financing mechanisms within the existing Startup Venture Building programme.

The national policy environment is favourable. The “Maroc IA 2030” strategy provides the strategic framework, the Al‑Jazari Institute network provides the institutional infrastructure, and the Startup Venture Building programme provides the financing. What is needed now is implementation—the translation of strategy into action, of policy into practice, and of theoretical roadmaps into deployed systems.

The call to action from this research is clear: launch the first IRU pilot within the Casablanca Aerospace City by 2027; implement the AI Innovation Voucher scheme within 12 months; certify the first cohort of Skills Passport holders within 18 months; and establish the regulatory sandbox to enable autonomous inspection deployment while the final DGAC framework is being gazetted.

Success will not be measured by the publication of this thesis alone, but by the tangible transformation of the Moroccan aerospace ecosystem: by the patents filed, the startups launched, the technicians upskilled, and the inspection times reduced. The foundations are in place. The roadmap is drawn. The time for action is now.